    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1980-01-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1980-01-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="341"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d341">
                <head>341. Memorandum From the Special Representative for Economic Summits
                        (<persName corresp="#p_OHD_1">Owen</persName>) to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJEJ_1">Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d341fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_CJEJ_1"
                            >Carter</persName> Library, National Security Affairs, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BZK_1">Brzezinski</persName> Material, Subject File, Box 25,
                        Foreign Assistance: 1–10/80. Confidential. Sent for information. In an
                        undated note to <persName corresp="#p_BZK_1">Brzezinski</persName>, under
                        cover of which he sent the memorandum for forwarding to <persName
                            corresp="#p_CJEJ_1">Carter</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_OHD_1"
                            >Owen</persName> wrote that he was “hopeful we can come up with large
                        increases in <gloss target="#t_PL480_1">PL 480</gloss> for both <gloss
                            target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 80 + <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 81,
                        which will help to calm farmers’ fears. But <gloss target="#t_OMB_1"
                            >OMB</gloss> is far from persuaded.” (Ibid.)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1980-01-11">January 11, 1980</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Aid Review (C)</item>
                </list>
                <p>An additional last minute fact that you should be aware of in reviewing aid
                    allocations to specific countries: We have just launched an inter-agency
                    exercise to see whether large additional amounts of grain (up to 1 million tons)
                    could be moved quickly as <gloss target="#t_PL_1">PL</gloss>–480 shipments <pb
                        facs="1114" n="1079" xml:id="pg_1079"/> overseas, in light of recent events.
                    Agriculture says that this would help reassure farmers. (C)</p>
                <p>I don’t know what recommendations will emerge, since there are some arguments
                    against such a program, but I do know that it would be impossible to move this
                    additional amount of <gloss target="#t_PL_1">PL</gloss>–480 grain without very
                    large additional shipments going to India and Bangladesh, as well as other
                    countries. South Asia is where most of the hungry people are. (C)</p>
                <p>If we do go forward with additional <gloss target="#t_PL_1">PL</gloss>–480
                    shipments to India and Bangladesh, and if we also cut back programmed <gloss
                        target="#t_AID_1">AID</gloss> development assistance to these countries, we
                    will seem to be increasing their food shipments and decreasing aid to help them
                    grow food at the same time. I suppose we could figure out how to answer
                    questions from the media and the Congress as to why we were moving in these
                    seemingly contradictory directions, but it would be hard. (C)</p>
                <p>The problem would be less difficult if we made any development aid cuts after the
                    Congressional appropriations reductions later in the year—when the announcement
                    of additional <gloss target="#t_PL_1">PL</gloss>–480 (if there is to be one)
                    will have faded from peoples’ minds. (C)</p>
            </div>
